description_PD: The use of nanosilica as a catalyst significantly enhances light-based curing in photopolymerization, reducing printing time from 4 seconds to 0.7 seconds per layer, thus accelerating the 3D printing process.
Digital light modulation enables precise control over the geometries and shape-shifting behavior of 3D printed shape memory polymers (SMPs), making it easier to create complex, functional devices.

The use of laser powder bed fusion (LPBF) enables precise thermal control, allowing designers to create 4D-printed NiTi alloys with tunable shape-memory behavior and enhanced mechanical properties for smart structures.

The intrinsic heat treatment (IHT) during laser additive manufacturing (LAM) enables the formation of strong, durable maraging steel without the need for additional post-processing, allowing designers to create high-performance parts more efficiently.
The 4D textile composite self-forms when exposed to heat, allowing designers to create complex shapes without additional programming steps, improving design flexibility and user interaction.

The temperature memory effect (TME) in the photopolymer allows product designers to create 4D-printed auxetic structures that autonomously reshape in response to heat, enabling dynamic and complex reconfigurations for innovative designs.

The use of a directional magnetic field during printing allows for the creation of flexible anisotropic soft-magnetic composites (FASMC) with enhanced and tunable magnetic properties, making it ideal for smart sensors, actuators, and other innovative devices.

The magnetic properties of the Fe3O4 nanocomposites enable remote control over shape changes, allowing designers to create smart 4D-printed objects that can be manipulated from a distance for innovative applications.

The blend's thermomechanical properties, influenced by the PBAT content, allow for better control of shape memory performance and faster shape recovery at lower transition temperatures, enabling the creation of more versatile and responsive 3D printed products.

The thermoplastic composites, such as PVC and PP, show varying shape memory properties when exposed to heat, allowing designers to tailor shape recovery and mechanical performance in 4D printed products.

description_PE: Nanosilica particles fine-tune the thermal properties of the resin, optimizing the curing process by reducing curing times and enhancing efficiency in 3D printing.

The process leverages digital light fabrication to tune the shape memory transition temperature and material properties, ensuring that the SMP can achieve its desired shape-shifting response with optimal thermal characteristics.

The laser scanning process in LPBF uses light to precisely manipulate the phase transformation and mechanical properties of NiTi alloys, improving both the material's functionality and the overall manufacturing process.

The unique cyclic thermal history in LAM facilitates in situ precipitation hardening, eliminating the need for post heat treatments (PHT) and optimizing the manufacturing process for high-strength materials like Fe-Ni-Ti-Al maraging steel.

The thermal stimulation process simplifies manufacturing by enabling the composite to automatically shape itself upon heating, eliminating the need for thermomechanical programming and enhancing production efficiency.

Heat serves as the key stimulus for triggering the controlled shape memory recovery process, allowing process engineers to program and fine-tune the deformation and recovery of 4D-printed auxetic grids over multiple steps.

The magnetic field-assisted digital light processing (MF-DLP) technique enables precise fabrication of FASMC with complex structures and high spatial resolution, overcoming the trade-offs between material properties and printability.

The temperature-induced shape-memory response of the nanocomposites enables precise control over the heat transfer during printing, optimizing the material's shape recovery and improving process efficiency in 3D and 4D printing.
The granule-based material extrusion process, driven by heat, allows precise control over the melt flow of PETG-PBAT blends, optimizing printability and ensuring uniform mechanical properties.
The thermal properties of PVC-PP blends, including their melting points, ensure optimal flowability and extrusion conditions, improving the 3D printing process and material handling.

description_MS: Nanosilica particles act as superior catalysts, enhancing light-based photopolymerization, while also reinforcing the polymer, improving mechanical properties and shape memory in 4D printed materials.

The heat-triggered shape memory transition temperature and tunable rubbery modulus allow fine control of the material’s mechanical and thermal properties, enabling advanced functionality in 3D printed devices.

The thermal treatment provided by controlled laser power influences the phase transformation from B2 to B19' in NiTi alloys, allowing for fine-tuning of their mechanical and functional properties in 4D printing applications.

The IHT effect in LAM enables in situ Ni3Ti precipitation within the martensitic matrix through fast precipitation kinetics, resulting in enhanced mechanical properties such as tensile strength and elongation in maraging steel.

The thermal responsiveness of the PLA and Lycra composite enables reversible transformations between permanent and temporary shapes, making it a versatile material for applications requiring adaptive shape memory behavior.

Heat activates the temperature memory effect (TME) in the photopolymer, enabling material scientists to explore and optimize the thermomechanical properties of the material for applications in tunable mechanical metamaterials.

The integration of carbonyl iron powder (CIP) into the resin, combined with magnetic field alignment, results in composites with high anisotropic magnetic properties, excellent tensile strength, and enhanced elongation capabilities, ideal for advanced material applications.

The addition of iron oxide nanoparticles enhances both the shape-memory effect and remote controllability through magnetic fields, providing a unique way to manipulate material properties for advanced performance in functional applications.

The thermomechanical compatibility between PETG and PBAT, particularly the transition temperature adjustments, strengthens the material's mechanical properties and enables better shape recovery through heat-driven processes.

The heat-driven thermal properties of PVC-PP composites, particularly their melting points and shape memory effects, allow for fine-tuning of material behavior, enabling enhanced shape recovery and mechanical strength.
